# {{ProjectName}}

This repository was generated from the MartiX Web API template and gives you a ready-to-run .NET 10 solution with:

- an API project (`src\{{ProjectName}}.Web`)
- shared service defaults (`src\{{ProjectName}}.ServiceDefaults`)
- optional Aspire orchestration (`src\{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost`, default: `--orchestrator aspire`)
- optional Blazor frontend (`src\{{ProjectName}}.Blazor`, default: `--frontend blazor`)
- a test project (`tests\{{ProjectName}}.Web.Tests`)

In this first conservative switch slice, `--frontend none` reuses the API-only Aspire host project (`src\{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost\{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost.NoBlazor.csproj`), and `--orchestrator none` scaffolds the direct API shape without the AppHost or frontend.

## Prerequisites

- .NET 10 SDK or later
- Docker Desktop or another compatible container runtime when you keep the Aspire workflow
- PowerShell or a POSIX shell if you want to run the scaffold helper scripts

## First-time setup

PowerShell:

```powershell
dotnet restore
dotnet build
dotnet test --solution .\{{ProjectName}}.slnx
```

Shell:

```sh
dotnet restore
dotnet build
dotnet test --solution ./{{ProjectName}}.slnx
```

If you want to materialize scaffold-managed repository docs such as `docs\SCAFFOLDING.md`, run:

PowerShell:

```powershell
.\scripts\bootstrap.ps1
```

Shell:

```sh
./scripts/bootstrap.sh
```

## Quality and governance

The generated GitHub baseline stays lightweight but still gives you practical
defaults for new repositories:

- `dotnet format whitespace --verify-no-changes` against the scaffolded `.editorconfig`
- Markdown linting for the scaffolded README, contributing/release docs, setup/troubleshooting/scaffolding docs, and PR template using `.markdownlint-cli2.jsonc`
- PowerShell syntax validation for generated `.ps1` scripts
- Release builds with warnings treated as errors, while leaving the current baseline exceptions (`CS1591`, `NU1902`, and `ASPIRE002`) visible as warnings
- test execution with Cobertura coverage output, while preserving raw results in `.artifacts\test-results` and publishing an HTML `coverage-report` artifact
- pull request title validation using Conventional Commits so squash-merged history stays compatible with semantic versioning
- Release Please automation on `main` and `master` that updates `CHANGELOG.md`, `version.txt`, and GitHub Releases from merged Conventional Commit history
- an optional token-gated quality-analysis workflow for Sonar and Qodana that stays idle until the repository is configured for it

The generated repository also includes a `global.json` entry that opts `dotnet test` into Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 10 SDKs, so local and CI test commands stay aligned.

See [`docs\SETUP.md`](docs/SETUP.md) for the local equivalents,
[`docs\RELEASE.md`](docs/RELEASE.md) for the release flow, and
[`docs\TROUBLESHOOTING.md`](docs/TROUBLESHOOTING.md) when one of those checks
fails.

## Supported template switches

The documented golden path is still the default:

- `dotnet new martix-webapi -n YourApp`
- `dotnet new martix-webapi -n YourApp --frontend none` keeps Aspire and drops the Blazor project
- `dotnet new martix-webapi -n YourApp --orchestrator none` drops the AppHost and, in this first iteration, also drops the frontend

## Run locally

### Full local experience with Aspire

Use this when you scaffolded the default `--orchestrator aspire --frontend blazor` path. It is the easiest local experience because it provisions SQL Server and Papercut for you.

PowerShell:

```powershell
dotnet run --project .\src\{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost\{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost.csproj
```

Shell:

```sh
dotnet run --project ./src/{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost/{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost.csproj
```

### API-only Aspire host

Use this when you scaffolded with `--frontend none` or when the default scaffold's built-in API-only host better fits the task.

PowerShell:

```powershell
dotnet run --project .\src\{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost\{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost.NoBlazor.csproj
```

Shell:

```sh
dotnet run --project ./src/{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost/{{ProjectName}}.AspireHost.NoBlazor.csproj
```

### Run the Web project directly

This is useful for focused API work and is the primary entry point when you scaffolded with `--orchestrator none`. The template includes a default development connection string in `src\{{ProjectName}}.Web\appsettings.json`, and you can override it with `ConnectionStrings__AppDb` when needed.

PowerShell:

```powershell
dotnet run --project .\src\{{ProjectName}}.Web\{{ProjectName}}.Web.csproj
```

Shell:

```sh
dotnet run --project ./src/{{ProjectName}}.Web/{{ProjectName}}.Web.csproj
```

## Database and configuration notes

- The API applies pending EF Core migrations on startup.
- `src\{{ProjectName}}.Web\appsettings.Development.json` currently enables `DatabaseOptions:RecreateOnStartup`, so development runs can recreate the database for a clean start.
- The default development connection string lives in `src\{{ProjectName}}.Web\appsettings.json`.
- Local overrides can come from environment variables, user secrets, or development-only config files.

